para.p:
Low resource language modeling often leverages multilingual pre-training, where a model is trained on multiple languages simultaneously (
            , 
          ).
Indeed, this can improve low-resource performance, particularly when models have sufficient capacity and the multilingual data is from related or typologically similar languages (
            , 
          ).
However, monolingual models have still been shown to achieve better performance than multilingual models for many languages (e.g. 
            , 
          ).
Thus, it appears that existing multilingual language models are still limited by model capacity or limited data in low-resource languages (
            , 
          ).

Notably, the training datasets for massively multilingual models are often heavily skewed towards high-resource languages.
For example, XGLM 4.5B is trained on over 7000

            ×

         more Norwegian (71GB; 5.4M native speakers) than Quechua (0.01GB; 7.3M native speakers; 
            , 
          ).
In a more extreme case, BLOOM is trained on only 0.07MB of Akan (8.1M native speakers) out of 1.61TB total (4e-6% of the pre-training dataset; 
            , 
          ).
These extremely small quantities of low-resource language data often do not leverage recent efforts to compile text data in low-resource languages (
            , 
          ), and the data imbalances are likely to severely hinder performance in low-resource languages.
Indeed, we find that these models have worse perplexities than simple bigram models for many languages (§).
Unfortunately, comparable monolingual language models across many diverse languages have yet to be studied or released.

